"You shall not be The grave of your deserving; Rome must know Worse than a theft, no less than a traducement, To hide your doings; and to silence that, Which, to the spire and top of praises vouch’d, Would seem but modest: therefore, I beseech you What you have done—before our army hear me.","Don’t dismiss the praise you deserve. Rome must know your value as her soldier. To conceal your achievements would be worse than stealing, and not less than slander, because for what you have done, no matter how highly we praise you, it will never be sufficient. So I ask you—in recognition of your importance to Rome, not to boast of your achievements—let me address you in front of our army."
